column1: Where will Dubai International Airport (DXB) rank among the busiest airports in the world by passenger number for 2020, according to the Airports Council International (ACI)?
column6: ['Business', 'Health']
Really difficult to find good news sources on this (all so clickbaity or US-centric). This may be my worst performance.

All ships rise (and fall) with the tide. Why do we feel DXB is dropping disproportionately vs the rest of the world?[1][2] The crowd is smart, and I followed the trend, but do we feel DXB is exceptional in terms of decline?...asking for a friend. Do you feel like a Cassandra, @Wildwood2000? If we go down with this ship, just know it was a pleasure forecasting with you tonight... [3]

Montreal, 19 May 2020 â€“ Airports Council International (ACI) World has today revealed its preliminary world airport traffic rankings covering passenger traffic, cargo volumes, and aircraft movements for 2019 combined with a glimpse of 2020 data which shows the dramatic impact of COVID-19 on airports in the first quarter.

No much flying lately! No one is jumping at the opportunity.

CNN reported in early October that Dubai traffic had dropped a whopping 56.4% since the beginning of 2020. More unbelievable than that, however, was that they dropped less than 8/9 other airports in the top 10 with only Dallas (number 10) dropping less. While things are beginning to open again and hubs like LAX and ATL will almost definitely come out ahead, it's hard to see it dropping below number 6 given the difficulties every other hub has had.
@cafebedouin your theory is sound, there is no way the whole ranking table will just shift lower by 60% in unison...
UAE flights resume after 6 months hiatus, from the aptly named BusiWeek media website (East African Business Week).
No change during the Covid-19 pandemic, but confirming Dubai's position as 4th.
Following @cafebedouin a bit to the very low end.

Crowd is wrong on this question. LAX was 3rd, right in front of Dubai in passenger traffic in 2019.[1] For January through June, LAX had 17.6 million passengers.[2] Dubai? 5 million.[3] Want to guess what's happening in all those Chinese airports? Is anyone doing international travel through Dubai? Yet, they are going to stay 4th to 6th to 84% probability? I don't think so.
6th now

Based on RRG and chiefthe's comments

For all of May, 44k passengers came through DXB, which would normally come through in a few hours [1]. The CEO is bullish on travel returning and numbers climbing, but while there is an increase in flights to even smaller destinations [2], and foreign flights are resuming [3], the other airports that are currently on the list are reporting higher numbers for May:

As Covid-19 will fundamentally change the way we travel, at the very least for the remainder of the year, I see a shift towards regional hubs like Paris, Amsterdam and Frankfurt or large domestic hubs like Denver, Chicago, Guangzhou at the expense of "intraregional" hubs such as Dubai or Singapore.
Airports spread Covid-19 like wildfire around the globe. The busiest airports in the world during the pandemic will curse their country with an unstoppable amount of plague.

Dubai is #4 now, but the lead vs #10 is just 14%. There are dozens of US and EU airports in the list. They will all be impacted less than Dubai. So low chance of 7-9 place and high chance of 10 or lower.
Lack of business and tourist travel - especially long haul flights
USA is in some serious trouble. Their airports in top 10 will probably not do well this year. Covid-19 and some kind of civil war that's starting.

All airports are going to be faced with social distancing and other measures that may limit traffic through them [1]. For the first quarter, the number of travelers were down by about 20% through Dubai [1]. The traffic for Dubai airport is heavily dependent (unsurprisingly) on flights by Emerates and flydubai, if looking only at destinations served [2]. Emerates started flying again to a selection of destinations as of May 21st [3]. Dubai was ranked 4th for Q1 for total passengers [4].

According to ACI latest data, Dubai airport stands at fourth place for the Q1 2020. If the Haj pilgrimage is cancelled, there are chances of further drop. The chances of moving up depends upon the position of Beijing airport.
Adjusting as a response to the crowd...

-Strict measures they apply-->probably opening up later than most EU countries&US to not undo their efforts. -Emirates in trouble, laying of employees, paying back customers, not flying,... -Possibility that the opening of EU&US and their travell will force Dubai to open up as well and undo their efforts. -Possibility that EU&US open up and there is no spike in cases and deaths(could be temporary, and spike again in winter), so no need to stay closed. -Possibility that they open up with strict measures like quarantaining incoming passengers but don't think a lot of foreign passengers are up for that. ...
Interesting question.

Knee-jerk prediction, will investigate further: Rationale being... expecting the rankings to be similar in structure; but lower in volume. Unless a hub/region becomes a C19 free utopia, how much can we expect the rankings to shuffle?
